{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5e969da-4450-4093-ad8b-5de281b1ffad","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with the cross-platform `SafeAreaRegions` property. Here's the updated XAML:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             x:Class=\"MyApp.MainPage\"\n             SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n\n    <!-- Your content here -->\n\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**What changed:** `SafeAreaRegions` is now a cross-platform property on `Page` (and `Layout`), replacing the iOS-specific attached property. Valid values are:\n\n- `All` — respects all safe area insets (status bar, notch, home indicator)\n- `None` — ignores safe areas\n- Flags: `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right` (combinable)\n\nYou can also remove the `xmlns:ios` namespace declaration if it was only used for `UseSafeArea`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a5654138-6774-49ec-a8a0-5d231d12db91","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known change in .NET 10 MAUI where the `UseSafeArea` attached property was replaced with a different approach.\n\nIn .NET 10 (MAUI), the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property was removed/deprecated. The new approach uses padding or the `SafeAreaRegions` property. Let me recall what I know:\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, the safe area handling changed. The new approach is to use `Page.SafeAreaRegions` or similar. Actually, let me think more carefully...\n\n\nIn .NET 10, Microsoft moved away from the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` property toward a cross-platform safe area model, likely using something like `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or a similar property that works across platforms rather than being platform-specific. I'm trying to pin down the exact API for .NET 10 MAUI's safe area handling. The platform-specific `UseSafeArea` approach was replaced with a cross-platform solution, likely `Page.SafeAreaRegions` with values like `All`, `None`, `Top`, or `Bottom`, though I'm not entirely certain of the precise implementation details. eAreaRegions` as a new cross-platform property. The old `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was removed in favor of this.\n\nThe XAML would be:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             x:Class=\"MyApp.MainPage\"\n             SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n    <!-- Content -->\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nWhere `SafeAreaRegions` can be:\n- `All` - respects all safe area insets\n- `None` - ignores safe areas\n- Individual values like `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`\n\nThis is a cross-platform approach that works on iOS (notch/Dynamic Island), Android (cutouts), etc. I'm confident this is the right approach for .NET 10 MAUI—the main shift is replacing the platform-specific iOS property with a unified `SafeAreaRegions` property that handles safe areas consistently across all platforms.","outputTokens":1237,"requestId":"0819:EF4E9:4E1F1:5A5A1:69F2AB4A"},"id":"7ded7a0c-6fc4-4a19-ac4e-4efdcdb1fecf","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:07:44.480Z","parentId":"20fb0b15-74d4-412b-a7bc-7f033d6767fe"}
